                    "created_at": "2025-05-24T13:08:51.640Z",
                    "cooked": "I have been playing with state space control in Robotpy. I now have a basic working example in the Magic Bot framework that simulates and controls an arbitrary arm mechanism based on my team’s intake for this year. It was a little tricky to get up to start with due to C++ templates not binding well to Python but I am working on that slowly.\n\nI have found a bit of an annoying, but I guess expected in hindsight, interaction between TrapezoidalProfile and KalmanFilter classes. An improperly initialised or poorly performing Filter can cook the setpoints produced by a trapezoidal profile, which in turn negatively impacts the rate at which the filter reconverges. Lose-Lose kinda situation. I have found the best way to handle this for now is to reset the filter after the predict step, but before a control command is sent. The ordering here is important. It guarantees that the realised behaviour closely matches what is being corrected for in the next step of the filter.\n\nI have started wondering what other guard rails I should consider to avoid totalling mechanisms during testing or ensuring that things remain operable during match play. A parallel I can think of on our robot is providing a designated relocalisation point on the field in case things get really bad. We spend most of our time driving in field-oriented mode and sometimes relative to a particular landmark or the robot. Both of the former break badly with poor localisation. The driver must recognise this situation and hobble off to the reset point. It’s generally not a problem anymore with April tags, but it was for a long while during the retroreflective tape era, where an absolute pose reference wasn’t guaranteed. I don’t think a similar reactive mitigation strategy makes sense on mechanisms because they are often too fast-moving, so preventative measures seem more appropriate.\n\nAre there any common place design philosophies that people use when dealing with these classes, or even any others? What are the gotchas a first-time user might run into around order of operations or similar?",
